---
import Layout from '../layouts/Layout.astro';
---
<Layout
  title="Montgomery County Deck Permits, Explained (2026 Guide) | Belvedere Decks"
  description="When you need an MCDPS deck permit in Montgomery County MD, what it costs, the three inspections, HOA review, and what happens if you skip it, from a builder who handles them for a living."
>
  <section class="hero">
    <div class="container">
      <p class="eyebrow">The homeowner's guide</p>
      <h1>Montgomery County deck permits, explained.</h1>
      <div class="rule"></div>
      <p class="lead">
        Half the deck builders ranking for Montgomery County searches are based far away. We work under the rules of Montgomery County’s building department (MCDPS) every week. Here's the guide we
        wish every homeowner read before collecting bids.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <section class="section">
    <div class="container">
      <h2>When you need a permit, and when you don't</h2>
      <table class="stack">
        <tbody>
          <tr><th>New deck</th><td>Permit required. Always.</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Demo and rebuild</th><td>Permit required. It's a new structure.</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Structural changes</th><td>Permit required for changes to framing, footings, or the ledger beyond in-kind repair.</td></tr>
          <tr><th>Deck Resurfacing</th><td>Typically no permit. Boards, railings, and edge trim are replaced but the frame stays. If frame repairs go beyond like-for-like replacement, we confirm with the county before proceeding.</td></tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>

      <h2>The three inspections</h2>
      <p>
        A permitted Montgomery County deck passes three checkpoints:
        <strong>footing inspection</strong>: the county checks your holes (30″ below
        grade, sized to code) before any concrete pours; <strong>framing
        inspection</strong>: the structure is checked before boards hide it; and the
        <strong>final inspection</strong> when everything is complete. Each is
        scheduled with the county at least 24 hours ahead, and we handle all three.
      </p>
      <p>
        The most-cited item on county deck inspections is the <strong>lateral load
        connection</strong>: the hardware that ties the deck to the house structure so
        it cannot pull away. It's cheap during construction and expensive to retrofit,
        and it's exactly the kind of line a low bid omits.
      </p>

      <h2>What permitting actually involves</h2>
      <p>
        The county fee is only the last step. Getting a deck legally approved means
        assembling the application package: the site information and plat, the
        structural details the county reviews, your HOA's architectural submission
        (drawings, material specs, and color selections in the format your HOA wants),
        the submission itself through the county's electronic system, and then
        coordinating all three inspections around the build schedule. That is real
        work, and it's why "we handle permitting" matters. Our pricing includes the
        entire process: paperwork, fees, submissions, and inspection scheduling. No
        surprise addendum, and nothing left for you to chase.
      </p>

      <h2>HOA architectural review</h2>
      <p>
        Most communities in Clarksburg, the Kentlands, and many Potomac and Olney
        subdivisions require HOA architectural approval on top of the county permit.
        The homeowner formally submits, but we prepare everything: drawings, material
        specs, and color selections in the format your HOA wants.
      </p>

      <h2>What happens if you skip it</h2>
      <p>
        Unpermitted structural work surfaces at the worst time, usually a home sale,
        when a buyer's inspector flags the deck and you're negotiating repairs on a
        deadline, or an insurance claim after a failure. Retroactive permits often mean
        opening up finished work. The permit is the cheap part.
      </p>

      <div class="notice">
        <strong>Our promise:</strong> we tell you in writing whether your project needs a
        permit, we pull it ourselves when it does, and we never suggest skipping one.
        A builder who offers to "save you the permit hassle" is saving themselves an
        inspection.
      </div>

      <p><a class="btn primary" href="/estimate">Ask us about your project</a></p>
    </div>
  </section>
</Layout>
